{
  "local_port": 36978,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How did you get into IIM?",
  "response": "Getting into an Indian Institute of Management (IIM) typically involves several steps, centered primarily around the Common Admission Test (CAT), which is the entrance exam for most IIMs. Here\u2019s a general overview of the process:\n\n1. **Preparation**: \n   - Many aspirants begin by preparing for the CAT exam, which tests quantitative ability, verbal ability, reading comprehension, data interpretation, and logical reasoning.\n   - Preparation can involve self-study, enrolling in coaching classes, and taking mock tests to improve speed and accuracy.\n\n2. **Taking the CAT Exam**: \n   - The CAT is usually held once a year. Candidates need to register and sit for the exam, which is computer-based.\n   - A high percentile in CAT is crucial as it significantly increases the chances of getting a call for the next stage of the admission process.\n\n3. **Application**: \n   - Candidates need to apply to the IIMs they are interested in, often during the CAT registration process.\n   - Each IIM has its own criteria for shortlisting candidates, which generally includes CAT scores, academic records, and sometimes work experience.\n\n4. **Shortlisting for Interviews**: \n   - Based on CAT scores and other criteria like past academic performance and work experience, candidates are shortlisted for the next round.\n   - IIMs call candidates for a Written Ability Test (WAT), Group Discussion (GD), and Personal Interview (PI).\n\n5. **WAT, GD, and PI**: \n   - In these stages, candidates are evaluated on their communication skills, managerial potential, and fit for the program.\n   - The written test assesses the ability to articulate thoughts clearly, while GD and PI typically evaluate communication and interpersonal skills.\n\n6. **Final Selection**: \n   - IIMs compile a composite score based on CAT scores, performance in WAT/GD/PI, academic diversity, gender diversity, and work experience.\n   - Offers for admission are extended to candidates based on their composite scores.\n\n7. **Acceptance and Enrollment**: \n   - Selected candidates receive admission offers, which they can accept to enroll in the program.\n\nEach IIM might tweak the exact process slightly, so it's important for aspirants to check the specific criteria and process on the official websites of the IIMs they\u2019re aiming for.",
